For a designer who has spent years catering to what audiences wanted—predominantly heavy Indian bridalwear in colourful brocades—the last year has been in Ashwin Thiyagarajan’s (@ashwin.thiyagarajan) own words, a “creative exhale”.
His latest bridalwear collection titled ‘Alar’ (which in Tamil means “full bloom”), is stripped of the rainbow array of colours that have so far marked his work and focuses on the white wedding wardrobe. It’s study in what he calls “soft structure”, where corseted waists meet sharp shoulders and floral motifs inspired by the hibiscus and jasmine gardens of his childhood overlap with geometric borders.
@patsyanthonyy in conversation with the diaspora-favourite designer from Chennai at the link in bio.
